Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Trim the @butternut squash{1}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the seeds (peel first if you prefer). Cut into 1cm chunks.

Pop the diced butternut onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and cooked through, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @green beans{150}, then cut into thirds.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} (see pantry for amount) into a medium #saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~rice{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Heat a large saucepan on medium heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @cashew nuts{25} and dry-fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Transfer to a #bowl{}, then pop the pan back on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Once hot, add the onion and stir-fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @tikka masala paste{75%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}, stirring continuously, then pour in the @water for the curry{150%ml}, @sugar{1} (see pantry for both amounts) and @vegetable stock paste{10}.

Stir the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and green beans into the curry, bring to a simmer, then lower the heat. Cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}.

Cook until the beans are tender and the chicken is cooked through, about ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the beans are tender, stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g} until completely combined. Remove from the heat if the butternut squash hasn't finished cooking yet. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Once cooked, stir the roasted squash through the curry.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your #bowls{}. Top with the creamy curry and sprinkle with the cashews to finish.

Enjoy!